Based on my research, here's a comprehensive overview of both technologies:

## **A2A (Agent-to-Agent) - Google**

### What It Is
The Agent2Agent (A2A) protocol is an **open communication standard** initially developed by Google and announced in April 2025. Google subsequently donated it to the Linux Foundation to make it an industry-wide open standard.

### Key Features & Capabilities
- **Agent Interoperability**: Enables AI agents built on different frameworks by different companies to communicate and collaborate seamlessly
- **Secure Communication**: Allows agents to securely exchange information and coordinate actions across enterprise systems
- **Cross-Platform**: Works across various systems and platforms, enabling multi-vendor agent development
- **Open Standard**: Now managed by the Linux Foundation, making it accessible to the entire AI industry

### Purpose & Use Cases
- Addresses the critical challenge of enabling generative AI agents to work together despite being built on diverse frameworks
- Enables complex multi-agent systems where different specialized agents collaborate
- Facilitates enterprise AI deployments where agents need to coordinate across different tools and platforms
- Supports building, deploying, and selling collaborative agent systems

### Current Status
- Announced in April 2025
- Contributed to the Linux Foundation in June 2025
- Actively being developed and upgraded by Google Cloud
- Available through Google's Agent Development Kit (ADK)
- Growing adoption as an industry standard

---

## **Agent Skills - Claude (Anthropic)**

### What It Is
Agent Skills is a **framework for teaching Claude specific capabilities** through packaged instructions. It's a declarative, prompt-based system that allows Claude to dynamically discover, learn, and execute specialized tasks.

### Key Features & Capabilities
- **Skill Packages**: Skills are simple folders containing instructions that teach Claude how to handle specific tasks or workflows
- **Pre-built Skills**: Anthropic provides ready-made skills for common document tasks (PowerPoint, Excel, Word, PDF)
- **Custom Skills**: Developers can create their own custom skills tailored to their specific needs
- **Dynamic Discovery**: Claude can discover and invoke skills on-demand using advanced tool use capabilities
- **Semantic Routing**: Claude automatically selects the best skill for each task

### Purpose & Use Cases
- Enable reliable coding, research, and data analysis workflows
- Provide agents with expert on-demand knowledge
- Allow users to teach Claude how they work, including their templates and processes
- Handle specialized document processing and manipulation tasks
- Execute tools dynamically to enable agents that take action in the real world

### Current Status
- Actively available on the Claude platform
- Documented in official Claude documentation
- Public repository available on GitHub (anthropics/skills)
- Educational course available through DeepLearning.AI
- Considered one of the most powerful features for customizing Claude's capabilities
- Part of Anthropic's broader Agent Skills standard (agentskills.io)

---

## **Key Differences**

- **Scope**: A2A focuses on **agent-to-agent communication** (interoperability), while Agent Skills focuses on **enhancing individual agent capabilities** (skill acquisition)
- **Level**: A2A operates at the **protocol/infrastructure level**, while Agent Skills operates at the **agent capability level**
- **Governance**: A2A is an **open industry standard** (Linux Foundation), while Agent Skills is **Anthropic's framework** (though with open components)
- **Complementary**: These technologies could work together - Agent Skills could enhance what individual agents can do, while A2A enables those skilled agents to communicate with each other
